'''''Rosalind Franklin''''', previously known as the '''ExoMars rover''', is a planned European robotic [[Mars rover]], part of the international [[astrobiology]] programme [[ExoMars]] led by the [[European Space Agency|European Space Agency (ESA)]]. The rover is named after [[Rosalind Franklin]], a British chemist and [[DNA]] research pioneer.<ref name="BBC-20190207">{{cite news |last=Amos |first=Jonathan |title=Rosalind Franklin: Mars rover named after DNA pioneer |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-47151778 |date=7 February 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=7 February 2019 }}</ref> ''Rosalind Franklin'' will be the first Mars rover to drill into a depth of up to two metres below the planet's surface.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Drilling into Mars |url=https://www.esa.int/ESA_Multimedia/Videos/2025/02/Drilling_into_Mars |access-date=2025-08-18 |website=www.esa.int |language=en}}</ref> The rover was designed to search for [[biomolecule]]s or [[biosignature]]s from past life. Its core task is to determine whether life ever existed on [[Mars]], or still does today.<ref>{{Cite web |title=All instruments onboard Rosalind Franklin rover |url=https://www.esa.int/Science_Exploration/Human_and_Robotic_Exploration/Exploration/ExoMars/All_instruments_onboard_Rosalind_Franklin_rover |access-date=2025-08-18 |website=www.esa.int |language=en}}</ref> As of 2026, ''Rosalind Franklin'' is expected to launch in 2028 on a [[Falcon Heavy]] rocket.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Foust |first=Jeff |date=17 April 2026 |title=NASA selects Falcon Heavy to launch ESA Mars rover mission despite budget threat |url=https://spacenews.com/nasa-selects-falcon-heavy-to-launch-esa-mars-rover-mission-despite-budget-threat/}}</ref> The rover, together with the [[Airbus]]-built<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Cowing |first=Keith |date=2025-03-31 |title=ExoMars Rosalind Franklin Astrobiology Rover Will Have A European Landing Platform |url=https://astrobiology.com/2025/03/exomars-rosalind-franklin-astrobiology-rover-will-have-a-european-landing-platform.html |access-date=2025-08-18 |website=Astrobiology |language=en-US}}</ref> landing platform EDLM,<ref name=":6">[https://eana-net.eu/conferences/EANA2025/abstract_show.php?id=27 ExoMars/Rosalind Franklin Mission Update]</ref> will travel to Mars inside the Descent Module, connected to the Carrier Module.<ref name=":1" /> The [[Trace Gas Orbiter]] (TGO), launched in 2016, will operate as the data-relay satellite of ''Rosalind Franklin''.<ref name="spacenews20120926">{{cite news |last=de Selding |first=Peter B. |date=3 October 2012 |title=U.S., Europe Won't Go It Alone in Mars Exploration |url=https://spacenews.com/us-europe-wont-go-it-alone-mars-exploration/ |access-date=28 January 2023 |work=Space News}}</ref>

== History ==

=== Overview ===
In mid-2010s, the mission was scheduled to launch in early 2020s in cooperation with the Russian [[Roscosmos State Corporation|Roscosmos]].<ref name="Vago">{{cite journal |last1=Vago |first1=Jorge |last2=Witasse |first2=Olivier |last3=Baglioni |first3=Pietro |last4=Haldemann |first4=Albert |last5=Gianfiglio |first5=Giacinto |last6=Blancquaert |first6=Thierry |last7=McCoy |first7=Don |last8=de Groot |first8=Rolf |display-authors=5 |date=August 2013 |title=ExoMars: ESA's Next Step in Mars Exploration |url=http://esamultimedia.esa.int/multimedia/publications/ESA-Bulletin-155/offline/download.pdf |journal=Bulletin |publisher=European Space Agency |issue=155 |pages=12–23}}</ref><ref name="LaunchMoved2020">{{cite press release |url=http://www.esa.int/For_Media/Press_Releases/Second_ExoMars_mission_moves_to_next_launch_opportunity_in_2020 |title=Second ExoMars mission moves to next launch opportunity in 2020 |publisher=European Space Agency |date=2 May 2016 |access-date=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref name="LaunchMoved2022">{{cite press release |url=http://www.esa.int/Newsroom/Press_Releases/ExoMars_to_take_off_for_the_Red_Planet_in_2022 |title=N° 6–2020: ExoMars to take off for the Red Planet in 2022 |publisher=[[ESA]] |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Russian invasion of Ukraine]] in 2022 caused a delay of the programme, as the member states of [[European Space Agency|ESA]] voted to terminate the cooperation.<ref name="auto1">{{cite news |title=Joint Europe-Russia Mars rover project is parked |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-60782932 |access-date=17 March 2022 |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Europe ending cooperation with Russia on life-hunting Mars rover |url=https://www.space.com/europe-ends-cooperation-russia-exomars-rover |publisher=Space.com}}</ref><ref name="sn-20220503">{{cite web |last=Foust |first=Jeff |url=https://spacenews.com/exomars-official-says-launch-unlikely-before-2028/ |title=ExoMars official says launch unlikely before 2028 |work=[[SpaceNews]] |date=3 May 2022 |access-date=5 May 2022}}</ref><ref name="Drahl">{{cite journal |last1=Drahl |first1=Carmen |title=The long-awaited mission that could transform our understanding of Mars |journal=Knowable Magazine |date=3 May 2023 |doi=10.1146/knowable-050323-1|doi-access=free |url=https://knowablemagazine.org/article/physical-world/2023/mission-could-transform-understanding-mars |access-date=9 May 2023 |language=en|url-access=subscription }}</ref> In 2024, the project received additional funding to restart and complete the mission with launch scheduled for 2028<ref name="auto">{{Cite web |last=Foust |first=Jeff |date=2024-04-10 |title=ESA awards contract to Thales Alenia Space to restart ExoMars |url=https://spacenews.com/esa-awards-contract-to-thales-alenia-space-to-restart-exomars/ |access-date=2024-04-11 |website=SpaceNews |language=en-US}}</ref> using a [[NASA]]-procured US launch vehicle and a new European landing platform.<ref name="nasa_launch">{{Cite web |title=NASA, European Space Agency Unite to Land Europe's Rover on Mars - NASA |url=https://www.nasa.gov/news-release/nasa-european-space-agency-unite-to-land-europes-rover-on-mars/ |access-date=2024-05-17 |language=en-US}}</ref> The landing is expected in 2030.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Landing sideways |url=https://www.esa.int/ESA_Multimedia/Videos/2026/05/Landing_sideways |access-date=2026-05-18 |website=www.esa.int |language=en}}</ref>

=== Origins ===
The rover was proposed in 2001 as part of ESA's [[Aurora Programme]]<ref>{{Cite news |last=esa |title=ExoMars frequently asked questions |url=http://www.esa.int/Our_Activities/Space_Science/ExoMars/ExoMars_frequently_asked_questions |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314164855/http://www.esa.int/Our_Activities/Space_Science/ExoMars/ExoMars_frequently_asked_questions |archive-date=2016-03-14 |access-date=2025-08-18 |work=European Space Agency |language=en-GB}}</ref> based on the [[astrobiology]] community's advice published in a 1999 document called the "Red Book".<ref name=":8">{{Cite web |title=The ExoMars project |url=https://www.russianspaceweb.com/exomars2018.html |access-date=2026-04-25 |website=www.russianspaceweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Scientific objectives of the ExoMars Rover - Robotic Exploration - Science Portal |url=https://sci.esa.int/web/mars/-/45082-rover-scientific-objectives |access-date=2026-04-25 |website=Robotic Exploration |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Key milestones in the ExoMars Programme - Robotic Exploration - Science Portal |url=https://sci.esa.int/web/mars/-/46137-programme-timeline |access-date=2026-04-29 |website=Robotic Exploration |language=en-US}}</ref> It was originally conceived as a 120-kg rover with a 10-kg science payload, launched in 2009 by a [[Soyuz-2-1b]] rocket from [[Soyuz at the Guiana Space Centre|Kourou]]. The [[Ariane 5]] and [[Proton (rocket family)|Proton]] rockets were also considered after the project was broadened in scope in mid-2000s.<ref name=":8" />

In 2009, ESA reached an agreement with [[NASA]] to launch the mission in 2018 together with NASA's [[Mars Astrobiology Explorer-Cacher|MAX-C]] rover using a US launch vehicle of the [[Atlas (rocket family)|Atlas family]].<ref name=":8" /> However, MAX-C was cancelled in April 2011 due to budget cuts in the US.<ref>{{cite news |last=de Selding |first=Peter B. |date=20 April 2011 |title=ESA Halts Work on ExoMars Orbiter and Rover |url=http://www.spacenews.com/civil/110420-esa-halts-work-exomars.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120524180452/http://www.spacenews.com/civil/110420-esa-halts-work-exomars.html |archive-date=May 24, 2012 |access-date=2011-04-21 |work=Space News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Svitak |first=Amy |date=18 April 2011 |title=U.S., Europe Plan Single-rover Mars Mission for 2018 |url=http://www.spacenews.com/civil/110418-single-rover-mars-mission-2018.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120524180453/http://www.spacenews.com/civil/110418-single-rover-mars-mission-2018.html |archive-date=May 24, 2012 |access-date=2011-04-21 |work=Space News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ori |first=G. G. |date=2010 |title=ExoMars and MAX-C: planning for potential cooperative science using 2-rover mission to Mars |url=https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2010epsc.conf..420O/abstract |journal=European Planetary Science Congress 2010 |language=en |pages=420 |bibcode=2010epsc.conf..420O }}</ref> At that time, the European rover was envisioned as weighing 270 kg and carrying a 14.4-kg science payload.<ref name=":8" />

In 2012, ESA entered negotiations about a new agreement with [[Roscosmos]] under which the Russian agency would provide a [[Proton (rocket family)|Proton]] launch vehicle and develop the descent module and the landing platform for the rover.<ref name=":8" /> The agreement was formalised in March 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |title=ExoMars: ESA and Roscosmos set for Mars missions - Robotic Exploration - Science Portal |url=https://sci.esa.int/web/mars/-/51495-exomars-esa-and-roscosmos-set-for-mars-missions |access-date=2026-04-25 |website=Robotic Exploration |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Spaceflight Now {{!}} Breaking News {{!}} ExoMars agreement signed by ESA and Russia |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/news/n1303/16exomars/ |access-date=2026-04-25 |website=spaceflightnow.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Bergin |first=Chris |date=2013-03-14 |title=ESA and Roscosmos sign ExoMars deal following NASA refocus |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2013/03/esa-roscosmos-sign-exomars-deal-nasa-refocus/ |access-date=2026-04-25 |website=NASASpaceFlight.com |language=en-US}}</ref> The rover's design reached its final configuration: an autonomous six-wheeled vehicle with mass approximately {{convert|300|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, about 60% more than NASA's 2004 [[Mars Exploration Rover]]s ''Spirit'' and ''Opportunity'',<ref name="mepag.jpl.nasa.gov">{{Cite conference |url=http://mepag.jpl.nasa.gov/meeting/mar-09/09_ExoMars_Status_MEPAG_09_Final.pdf |title=ExoMars Status |conference=20th Mars Exploration Program Analysis Group Meeting. 3–4 March 2009. Arlington, Virginia. |publisher=European Space Agency |first1=J. L. |last1=Vego |display-authors=etal |year=2009 |access-date=15 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409170116/http://mepag.jpl.nasa.gov/meeting/mar-09/09_ExoMars_Status_MEPAG_09_Final.pdf |archive-date=9 April 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> but about one third that of NASA's later rovers: [[Curiosity (rover)|''Curiosity'']], launched in 2011, and [[Perseverance (rover)|''Perseverance'']], launched in 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://exploration.esa.int/mars/45787-rover-surface-operations/ |title=Rover surface operations |publisher=European Space Agency |date=18 December 2012 |access-date=16 March 2012}}</ref><ref name="Astro2017">{{cite journal |title=Habitability on Early Mars and the Search for Biosignatures with the ExoMars Rover |journal=[[Astrobiology (journal)|Astrobiology]] |first=Jorge L. |last=Vago |display-authors=etal |volume=17 |issue=6–7 |pages=471–510 |date=July 2017 |doi=10.1089/ast.2016.1533 |pmid=31067287 |bibcode=2017AsBio..17..471V|pmc=5685153 }}</ref><ref name="Press-Info">{{cite press release |url=https://www.thalesgroup.com/en/content/press-info-exomars-status |title=Press Info: ExoMars Status |publisher=Thales Group |date=8 May 2012 |access-date=8 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203010438/https://www.thalesgroup.com/en/content/press-info-exomars-status |archive-date=3 December 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="Instruments">{{cite web |url=http://www.esa.int/SPECIALS/ExoMars/SEMSZIAMS7F_0.html |title=The ExoMars Instruments |publisher=European Space Agency |date=1 February 2008 |access-date=8 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026132118/http://www.esa.int/SPECIALS/ExoMars/SEMSZIAMS7F_0.html |archive-date=26 October 2012}}</ref><ref name="still keen">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-17390576 |title=Europe still keen on Mars missions |work=BBC News |first=Jonathan |last=Amos |date=15 March 2012 |access-date=16 March 2012}}</ref> The mission completed its System Requirements Review (SRR) in July 2013<ref name=":8" /><gallery mode="packed">
